</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31AF981C1524A63CCA3F3D39EB763A8" pageId="3" pageNumber="307" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="8BBFAA0AC1524A63CCA3F3D39EB763A8" blockId="3.[1435,2665,2417,3474]" pageId="3" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis id="B9747618C1524A63CCA3F3D39055635B" bold="true" box="[1459,2172,3126,3159]" pageId="3" pageNumber="307">Movements, Home range and Social organization.</emphasis>
The Sumatran Porcupine is common and can occur at higher densities in secondary or disturbed habitats than in primary habitats.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C31AF981C1524A63CCA3F3499F9A624E" pageId="3" pageNumber="307" type="conservation">
<paragraph id="8BBFAA0AC1524A63CCA3F3499F9A624E" blockId="3.[1435,2665,2417,3474]" pageId="3" pageNumber="307">
<emphasis id="B9747618C1524A63CCA3F3499F3C63C1" bold="true" box="[1459,1813,3244,3277]" pageId="3" pageNumber="307">Status and Conservation.</emphasis>
Classified as Least Concern on The IUCN Red List. The Sumatran Porcupine is hunted for food, but hunting it not a serious conservation threat. Endemic island rodents such as the Sumatran Porcupine may be particularly at risk of extinction and require further study.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
